cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|I prefer the 3@C as the negative bid over a 2@H or 2@S rebid. It does very occasionally give responder an awkward problem when he has a good hand with clubs and no support for partner's suit. But even if that happens, most often the contract ends up in opener's suit anyway so no real harm is done if responder is forced to either underbid 3@C, bid 2N, or raise with 2-card support.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

Therefore, using Howard's standard, your bid in either case with that real gem of a hand is 3@C.|cs||cp||fp||ht|f|cp||cs|6|at|^B {|ia|,2cp2dp2sp3c|at|}|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


ht|v|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Responder should only bid 3@C when he has no aces or kings, fewer than 6 HCP, and less than 3-card support for opener's suit. If he has a weak hand but 3+ card support he should jump to 4 of a major. Thus the auction 2@C-2@D-2@H-4@H is an example of "fast arrival" showing a weak hand with heart support. The auction 2@C-2@D-2@H-3@H shows that responder has a stronger hand with at least 1 ace or king or 6+ HCP (slow arrival) and is potentially interested in slam.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

