cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|In the past and even now, some people liked the idea of responder being able to still show a really bad hand, and played 2@H as the "negative" or "bust" bid. I played that for many years, and it is still played by many.

The main problem with playing 2H shows a bust hand is when the 2@C bidder's suit is hearts. The contract is wrong sided (e.g. the weak hand ends up as declarer because of the artificial 2@H bid). And the auction gets too high too fast. The auction starts 2@C-2@H-3@H, where 3@H is the first natural bid and the 2@H bid has preempted the partnership. On that auction you are pretty much committed to playing 4@H and have little chance of getting to 3N when that is the best contract. It is because of this problem that I strongly prefer not to play 2H as showing a bust hand.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

A second problem with playing 2@H shows a bust is when responder has a nice heart suit (5+ cards with 2 of the 3 top honors). Some pairs play that a 2N bid is used to show that hand. The problem is, when opener has spades, he has to show them at the 3-level, taking up valuable bidding room. Others play that you simply bid 2@D over 2@C with that hand and show the hearts later.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


AT|

